    <text>
        <front>
            <div type="abstract">
                <p tid="1">Commentaries and liturgical works related to the mother tantras, centered on a range of deities divided into
                    six main families (Toh 1401-1783)</p>
            </div>
        </front>
        <body>
            <div type="article">
                <head type="article" tid="6">Wisdom tantra</head>
                <div type="section" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21615-article-1">
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21615-1"/>
                    <p tid="2">Wisdom, or “mother” tantras (<foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">ma’i rgyud</foreign>), are a subset of Unexcelled
                        Yoga tantras in which, it is said, the emphasis is on wisdom more than skillful means, the profound more
                        than the vast, seeing the deity as the channels, energies and essences more than as the aggregates,
                        elements, and sense-fields, relying more on the practice of <foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">gtum mo</foreign>
                        and bliss than on practices of the channels and energies, and in which female deities are more numerous
                        than male. They are often also called yoginī tantras (<title xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">rnal ’byor ma’i
                            rgyud</title>).</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21615-2"/>
                    <p tid="3">The 383 Tengyur works placed in this category by the <foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">dkar chag</foreign> are
                        here divided for convenience into two groups: </p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21615-3"/>
                    <p tid="4">I. the 206 works on the tantras related to Śaṃvara or Cakrasaṃvara and his consort Vajrayoginī or
                        Vajravārāhī (Toh 1401-1606); and</p>
                    <milestone unit="chunk" xml:id="O1JC76301JC21615-4"/>
                    <p tid="5">II. the 177 works on the other wisdom tantras, those of Catuḥpīṭha, Mahāmāyā, Vajrāmṛta, Buddhakapāla,
                        Buddhasamayoga, and Tāra (Toh 1607-1783).</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </body>
